[Apologies for multiple postings]

AISB SYMPOSIUM ON MULTIMODAL OUTPUT GENERATION (MOG 2008)
3 and 4 April 2008, Aberdeen, Scotland, UK =
http://www.csd.abdn.ac.uk/~ivdsluis/mog2008/


SYMPOSIUM PURPOSE

An important aspect of the new generation of intelligent systems is the=20
possibility to employ more than one output modality when interacting=20
with the user. A quick and successful interaction is expected when, for=20
instance, the system's output is presented to the user via=20
multimedia/hypermedia in which text and graphics are merged, or by a=20
conversational agent that combines the use of speech and gesture. In=20
such multimodal systems sophisticated specifications are needed to=20
combine the different output modalities in such a way that each bit of=20
information is presented in the most appropriate manner (i.e., the=20
system should select the most suitable modalities and modality=20
combinations to convey information to the user).

The AISB symposium MOG 2008 aims to bring work on multimodal output=20
generation from different disciplines together to establish common=20
ground and discuss possible future collaborations. Besides contributions =

from research fields such as multimodal language generation and embodied =

conversational agents, we would like to bring in an additional angle by=20
investigating how research on multimodal output generation can benefit=20
from a non-engineering perspective on multimodality. For example, how=20
can research done in psychology and cognitive sciences, related to=20
understanding how humans perceive and process multimodal information, be =

properly formalized for the purposes of intelligent multimodal output=20
generation? And to what extent is it possible to formalize existing=20
theories about how meaning is made in multimodal communication (the=20
semiotic perspective, represented by our guest speaker Prof. Eija=20
Ventola) and use that for generating more meaningful multimodal output=20
in the context of intelligent systems?

Thus, we invite technically oriented contributions as well as work in=20
the area of human communication, such as cognitive models of multimodal=20
communication and interaction. This way, we hope to combine an=20
AI/engineering perspective with input from other disciplines such as=20
linguistics and psychology, providing a forum where international=20
researchers from different disciplinary backgrounds can exchange ideas=20
on multimodal output generation and engage in scientific research=20
collaboration.

MOG 2008 is a follow-up of MOG 2007, the workshop on Multimodal Output=20
Generation organized on January 25-26, 2007, at the University of =
Aberdeen.

SYMPOSIUM FORMAT

The symposium will take place in two consecutive days. Note that this is =

provisional depending on the number of submissions. Apart from the talks =

in which the participants present their work there will also be central=20
discussions that should result in useful strategies for future work. All =

accepted papers will have a poster space on the same day as their paper=20
presentation.

SYMPOSIUM TOPICS

We welcome submissions on issues such as modality choice, integration of =

output modalities, and meaning representation for multimodal output=20
generation, where natural language (in the form of either text or=20
speech) is one of the modalities. We aim to have a varied programme that =

reflects the different research fields involved in multimodal output=20
generation. Possible topics are listed below, but this list is not=20
intended to be exhaustive.

     * task-based modality choice (domain and data dependencies)
     * user-based modality choice (constraints, preferences and =
expertise)
     * cross-references between modalities (e.g., text and graphics)
     * dependencies between modalities (e.g., speech, mimics and =
gestures)
     * relation between input and output modalities
     * integration of modalities (models, levels, dependencies)
     * cognitive models for processing multimodal information
     * computational models for multimodal output generation
     * models of modality integration based on multimodal discourse =
analysis
     * usability and evaluation of existing models
     * knowledge representation for multimodal output generation
     * evaluation of (methods for generating) multimodal output
     * development of multimodal corpora from a generation perspective


INVITED SPEAKERS

Eija Ventola (University of Helsinki)
Second invited speaker to be announced.

PAPER SUBMISSION DETAILS

We invite both long papers describing mature research (max. 8 pages) and =

short papers (max. 4 pages) describing plans, ideas and demos, which=20
could invoke discussion and questions to be addressed in the future.

Accepted papers will be published in the AISB proceedings, with an ISBN=20
number. Authors must sign a non-exclusive copyright declaration which=20
gives AISB the right to publish the paper, but does not prevent the=20
author from also publishing it in other venues after.

We intend to publish a special issue journal or book collection (e.g.,=20
LNCS or LNAI) based on a selection of the best papers from MOG 2007 and=20
MOG 2008.

Paper formatting instructions and templates can be downloaded here:
http://www.aisb.org.uk/convention/aisb08/download.html

Papers can be submitted by e-mail to: mog2008<at>ewi.utwente.nl=20
(Substitute @ sign for <at>)


IMPORTANT DATES

     * Submission of papers: January 7, 2008
     * Notification: February 15, 2008
     * Full paper deadline: March 16, 2008
     * Symposium dates: April 3-4, 2008

(Note that the symposium dates are provisional, subject to the number of =

final accepted papers.)


SYMPOSIUM ORGANISERS

     * Mari=EBt Theune, University of Twente, The Netherlands
     * Yulia Bachvarova, University of Twente, The Netherlands
     * Elisabeth Andr=E9, University of Augsburg, Germany
     * Ielka van der Sluis, University of Aberdeen, UK


PROGRAMME COMMITTEE

     * Adrian Bangerter, University of Neuchatel, Switzerland
     * Ellen Gurman Bard, University of Edinburgh, UK
     * John Bateman, University of Bremen, Germany
     * Harry Bunt, Tilburg University, The Netherlands
     * Justine Cassell, Northwestern University, US
     * Stephan Kopp, University of Bielefeld, Germany
     * Emiel Krahmer, Tilburg University, The Netherlands
     * Theo van Leeuwen, University of Technology Sydney, Australia
     * Anton Nijholt, University of Twente, The Netherlands
     * Jon Oberlander, University of Edinburgh, UK
     * Niels Ole Bernsen, University of Southern Denmark
     * Ehud Reiter, University of Aberdeen, UK
     * Jan Peter de Ruiter, Max Planck Institute, The Netherlands
     * Jacques Terken, Eindhoven University, The Netherlands
     * Eija Ventola, University of Helsinki, Finland
     * Ipke Wachsmuth, University of Bielefeld, Germany

SPONSORS AND ENDORSEMENT

The MOG 2008 Symposium is sponsored by the research project IMOGEN:=20
http://wwwhome.cs.utwente.nl/~theune/IMOGEN/

MOG 2008 is endorsed by:
- SIGGEN, the ACL Special Interest Group on Generation
- SIGMEDIA, the ACL Special Interest Group on Multimedia Language=20
Processing.


AISB 2008

The MOG 2008 Symposium is part of the AISB 2008 Convention on=20
Communication, Interaction and Social Intelligence, April 1-4, 2008,=20
Aberdeen, Scotland. For information on travel, accommodation, and=20
registration see the AISB 2008 website:=20
http://www.aisb.org.uk/convention/aisb08/

Note that there is an AISB best student paper award, and student=20
scholarships are available:=20
http://www.aisb.org.uk/convention/aisb08/scholarships.html

