SYMPOSIUM ON MULTIMODAL OUTPUT GENERATION (MOG 2008)<BR>3 and 4 April =
2008,=20
Aberdeen, Scotland, UK <A=20
href=3D"http://www.csd.abdn.ac.uk/~ivdsluis/mog2008/">http://www.csd.abdn=
.ac.uk/~ivdsluis/mog2008/</A><BR><BR><BR>SYMPOSIUM=20
PURPOSE<BR><BR>An important aspect of the new generation of intelligent =
systems=20
is the <BR>possibility to employ more than one output modality when =
interacting=20
<BR>with the user. A quick and successful interaction is expected when, =
for=20
<BR>instance, the system's output is presented to the user via=20
<BR>multimedia/hypermedia in which text and graphics are merged, or by a =

<BR>conversational agent that combines the use of speech and gesture. In =

<BR>such multimodal systems sophisticated specifications are needed to=20
<BR>combine the different output modalities in such a way that each bit =
of=20
<BR>information is presented in the most appropriate manner (i.e., the=20
<BR>system should select the most suitable modalities and modality=20
<BR>combinations to convey information to the user).<BR><BR>The AISB =
symposium=20
MOG 2008 aims to bring work on multimodal output <BR>generation from =
different=20
disciplines together to establish common <BR>ground and discuss possible =
future=20
collaborations. Besides contributions <BR>from research fields such as=20
multimodal language generation and embodied <BR>conversational agents, =
we would=20
like to bring in an additional angle by <BR>investigating how research =
on=20
multimodal output generation can benefit <BR>from a non-engineering =
perspective=20
on multimodality. For example, how <BR>can research done in psychology =
and=20
cognitive sciences, related to <BR>understanding how humans perceive and =
process=20
multimodal information, be <BR>properly formalized for the purposes of=20
intelligent multimodal output <BR>generation? And to what extent is it =
possible=20
to formalize existing <BR>theories about how meaning is made in =
multimodal=20
communication (the <BR>semiotic perspective, represented by our guest =
speaker=20
Prof. Eija <BR>Ventola) and use that for generating more meaningful =
multimodal=20
output <BR>in the context of intelligent systems?<BR><BR>Thus, we invite =

technically oriented contributions as well as work in <BR>the area of =
human=20
communication, such as cognitive models of multimodal <BR>communication =
and=20
interaction. This way, we hope to combine an <BR>AI/engineering =
perspective with=20
input from other disciplines such as <BR>linguistics and psychology, =
providing a=20
forum where international <BR>researchers from different disciplinary=20
backgrounds can exchange ideas <BR>on multimodal output generation and =
engage in=20
scientific research <BR>collaboration.<BR><BR>MOG 2008 is a follow-up of =
MOG=20
2007, the workshop on Multimodal Output <BR>Generation organized on =
January=20
25-26, 2007, at the <st1:place w:st=3D"on"><st1:PlaceType=20
w:st=3D"on">University</st1:PlaceType> of <st1:PlaceName=20
w:st=3D"on">Aberdeen</st1:PlaceName></st1:place>.<BR><BR>SYMPOSIUM=20
FORMAT<BR><BR>The symposium will take place in two consecutive days. =
Note that=20
this is <BR>provisional depending on the number of submissions. Apart =
from the=20
talks <BR>in which the participants present their work there will also =
be=20
central <BR>discussions that should result in useful strategies for =
future work.=20
All <BR>accepted papers will have a poster space on the same day as =
their paper=20
<BR>presentation.<BR><BR>SYMPOSIUM TOPICS<BR><BR>We welcome submissions =
on=20
issues such as modality choice, integration of <BR>output modalities, =
and=20
meaning representation for multimodal output <BR>generation, where =
natural=20
language (in the form of either text or <BR>speech) is one of the =
modalities. We=20
aim to have a varied programme that <BR>reflects the different research =
fields=20
involved in multimodal output <BR>generation. Possible topics are listed =
below,=20
but this list is not <BR>intended to be=20
exhaustive.<BR><BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; * task-based modality choice =
(domain=20
and data dependencies)<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; * user-based modality =
choice=20
(constraints, preferences and expertise)<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *=20
cross-references between modalities (e.g., text and=20
graphics)<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; * dependencies between modalities =
(e.g.,=20
speech, mimics and gestures)<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; * relation =
between=20
input and output modalities<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; * integration of =

modalities (models, levels, dependencies)<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *=20
cognitive models for processing multimodal=20
information<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; * computational models for =
multimodal=20
output generation<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; * models of modality =
integration=20
based on multimodal discourse analysis<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; * =
usability=20
and evaluation of existing models<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; * =
knowledge=20
representation for multimodal output =
generation<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *=20
evaluation of (methods for generating) multimodal=20
output<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; * development of multimodal corpora =
from a=20
generation perspective<BR><BR><BR>INVITED SPEAKERS<BR><BR>Eija Ventola=20
(University of Helsinki)<BR>Second invited speaker to be =
announced.<BR><BR>PAPER=20
SUBMISSION DETAILS<BR><BR>We invite both long papers describing mature =
research=20
(max. 8 pages) and <BR>short papers (max. 4 pages) describing plans, =
ideas and=20
demos, which <BR>could invoke discussion and questions to be addressed =
in the=20
future.<BR><BR>Accepted papers will be published in the AISB =
proceedings, with=20
an ISBN <BR>number. Authors must sign a non-exclusive copyright =
declaration=20
which <BR>gives AISB the right to publish the paper, but does not =
prevent the=20
<BR>author from also publishing it in other venues after.<BR><BR>We =
intend to=20
publish a special issue journal or book collection (e.g., <BR>LNCS or =
LNAI)=20
based on a selection of the best papers from MOG 2007 and <BR>MOG=20
2008.<BR><BR>Paper formatting instructions and templates can be =
downloaded=20
here:<BR><A=20
href=3D"http://www.aisb.org.uk/convention/aisb08/download.html">http://ww=
